Annual Returning Student Registration.

Don‚Äôt delay confirm your student will be returning to the LWSD for the 2020-21 school year!

Parents/guardians who are designated as ‚Äúprimary guardians‚Äù are being asked to log into Family Access and complete the Returning Student Registration for each child currently enrolled in the district. To prevent redundant or conflicting data updates, only primary guardians will need to update the Returning Student Registration information in Family Access.

Please take the time to review your contact information and make any necessary updates. In order for us to communicate efficiently with each parent, it is vital that you provide the district with your most current contact information.

If you are not planning on your student returning, please contact the district office to complete the withdraw paperwork required.

For any questions regarding verification, registration, or login information please contact the district office at 360-652-4500

post_text:
Who can receive P-EBT?

Students enrolled in a K-12 school that offers a school lunch program during the normal school year AND

Is eligible for free or reduced-price school meals OR

Is attending a school where meals are free for all students such as a Provision 2 or Community Eligibility Provision School.

Visit K12.wa.us/PEBT for more information and WashingtonConnection.org to apply!

post_text:
Looking ahead to the 2020-21 school year, the Lakewood School District is developing plans for a variety of scenarios and an effective back-to-school transition. Your feedback is essential. To get your perceptions, we are partnering with the Center for Educational Effectiveness (CEE) who will administer the EES-Reopening Survey‚Ñ¢ to all stakeholders.

Staff, student, and parent perceptions will be gathered around:
‚Ä¢ Safe & Supported Learning Environment
‚Ä¢ Transportation & Food Safety
‚Ä¢ Teaching & Learning
‚Ä¢ Access & Engagement
‚Ä¢ Scheduling & Staffing

Lakewood School Opening Survey: Parent/Guardian
To gather this information, we are asking that you take 10 minutes to complete this survey by clicking on the link below. If you have students in more than one building you are encouraged to complete the survey for each student. Survey will close on 6/17/2020.

Survey Link: https://www.research.net/r/lakewood-parent

Survey Link: https://www.research.net/r/lakewood-student

The survey is confidential and anonymous. Thank you for your feedback!

post_text: English Crossing Elementary is one of 319 schools being recognized as part of the Washington State School Recognition Week. Schools across the state are being recognized for showing excellence in three areas; closing gaps and showing tremendous growth and achievement. English Crossing is being recognized for demonstrating growth during the 2018-2019 in two areas. growth for students identifying as Hispanic and growth for students who qualify for free and reduced-priced meals. We are extremely proud of our students, teachers, and the entire school community for the continued commitment to excellence.

Health Care Professionals

post_text:
New and Reelected Board Members Sworn Into Office

At the December 4, 2019, Lakewood Board of Director‚Äôs meeting Steven Larson was sworn into office replacing Jeremy Toponce representing Lakewood School Director District #1. He will finish out the term until 2021. Leaha Boser was reelected to represent Director District #4 and Lawrence Bean was reelected for Director District #5 for a full term until 2023.

Mr. Larson has lived in the community for the past fifteen years. He is employed with Boeing and is currently raising his Grand Nephews that attend Lakewood Schools. He is a US Army Veteran, Eagle Scout, Assistant Cubmaster with Cub Scout Pack 92, and has volunteered at LYFAA football games.

We are delighted to have our returning board members and the addition of Steven. He has been an active supporter of the Lakewood School District and we are pleased to welcome him into his new role as a board member!

post_text:
Good morning,

As you may recall, approximately one month ago, our district administration and law enforcement investigated an Instagram posting that referenced an online rumor concerning a Dec. 2nd shooting in a community named Lakewood. Our investigation found no direct threat to our students or schools. The investigation did not link the original rumor or message to anyone associated with our schools.

As a precaution, we have requested an enhanced law enforcement presence today in our district. In addition, we will be providing additional administrative support to all of our buildings. The safety of Lakewood staff and students is paramount. Threats to safety and security will always be taken seriously.

Sincerely,
Scott M. Peacock

School bus transportation plays a critical role in the education of our nation's students and is the direct link between a neighborhood and the classroom. More than 25 million children ride the yellow bus every school day, and National School Bus Safety Week serves as a reminder for students, parents, teachers, and the community to keep school bus safety at the forefront.

Thank you to our transportation department for safely transporting students to and from school!

This message is to inform you that we are revising the start and stop times at our middle and high school by five minutes.

Lakewood High School will now begin and end 5 minutes later than it has in prior years. The new start/stop time will be 7:35- 2:15.

Lakewood Middle School will now begin and end 5 minutes earlier than it has in prior years. The new start/stop time will be 7:30- 2:10.

This switch is to better align our transportation drop-offs and pick-ups at both the middle and high school. This change does not affect transportation route times.

post_text:
NEW LMS PRINCIPAL SELECTED

It is with great enthusiasm that we announce Amanda Cote as the next principal of Lakewood Middle School. Amanda has been an assistant principal at Centennial Middle School in the Snohomish School District for the past five years. Prior to serving as an administrator, she worked in Snohomish, along with several other school districts around the United States, as a social studies and language arts teacher. She has had the privilege of working in several districts due to the fact that her husband served in the military.

Amanda was selected from a terrific pool of applicants and two experienced finalists. She brings a strong commitment to instructional improvement in multiple content areas, experience in multiple areas of special education (including work with students who have behavioral disabilities and autism), as well as a background supporting the social-emotional learning of students.

It is our pleasure to welcome Amanda Cote to the Lakewood team and community.

Hopefully, everyone is safe and secure following the earthquake. Such an event serves as a reminder of how fragile things can be in the face of nature‚Äôs power.

We wanted you to know that upon arriving to work on Friday in the hours following the earthquake, our maintenance and custodial staff engaged in a visual inspection of all schools and classrooms. We are relieved to note that we found no damage that can be attributed to the earthquake. As always, we remain focused on ensuring that our schools are safe and positive places for students, staff and the community.

Have a great summer. Stay safe.

Transportation Notification:
Lakewood Transportation will be altering our route numbering process.

Starting at the end of May, buses will be given a new route designation. This route number will stay consistent year to year regardless of which bus is assigned to that area. The route number will be on a sign next to the service door. We currently use these signs for our spare buses so the students are familiar with this procedure already. We will also be placing the route number in the bus for the students to see routinely. This process will be fully implemented by the beginning of September, next school year.

Lakewood Transportation's goal is to transport your child to and from school safely. Reducing confusion is one way to achieve this. We appreciate your assistance as we make this transition. Feel free to contact transportation if you have any comments, questions or concerns at 360-652-4525

post_text: This school year, Lakewood School District has been offering ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù courses to its staff members. The course is taught by Lakewood‚Äôs District Nurse, Kelsey Mitchell MSN, BSN, RN, who is a licensed ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù instructor. Thus far, over 100 staff members have received life-saving ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù training, including numerous coaches. The ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù course teaches participants how to recognize and respond to life-threatening bleeding. Through hands-on practice, class participants learn how to apply compression, pack wounds, and apply tourniquets. After completion of the course, attendees also walk-away with their own ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù kit to keep in their classroom or their coaching bag. Each kit contains a tourniquet, hemostatic gauze, a compression bandage, gloves, and trauma shears. The district will continue to offer more ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù courses in the future in order to further strengthen the safety and security of students and staff.

Today our 1st-grade students from English Crossing Elementary accompanied by Librarian, Molly Pearson visited the Smokey Point/Lakewood Sno-Isle Library. The Sno-Isle librarians had a wonderful program planned, it included stories, a scavenger hunt, and check out. Prior to the visit parents completed library card applications for the students so part of the program included handing out their very first library card. Most came home with two books, and they had a wonderful time.

Our 6th and 7th graders attended a similar program with our LMS/LHS Librarian, Lauren Weeks back in January. Lakewood Elementary and Cougar Creek have upcoming trips scheduled with their librarians, Ashley Bailey, and Stephanie Davis.

Thank you to all those involved in helping to make these successful field trips for our Lakewood students.

Congratulations to our Lakewood High School Jazz Band "11th Avenue" who took 1st place in the largest division at the 44th Annual Pleasant Hill Jazz Festival Invitational. Music Director Katy Trapp stated, "these kids have worked so incredibly hard for this and truly earned this trophy". 11th Avenue competed against 10 tough competitors and our 3-year-old jazz band was the youngest jazz band program by over a decade in the competition.

LHS Jazz also brought home 2 festival solo awards. In the instrumental division, a Solo Award went to Alex Williams. In the vocal division, a Solo Award went to Julia Williams.

Please join us in congratulating all of these young musicians. This is a huge accomplishment for our LHS music students and LHS Music Department Director, Katy Trapp.

As of January 24, 2019, there has been a total of 26 confirmed and probable cases of the measles in Washington State. Of these 26 cases, 1 is in King County and 25 are in Clark County. Student and staff exclusions have now been implemented in impacted schools.

At this point in time, there have been NO confirmed or probable cases of the measles in Lakewood School District. However, in light of the growing measles outbreak across Washington State, we wanted to notify you of our District policies regarding a vaccine-preventable communicable disease outbreak.

Please visit our district website for more information.

post_text:
Now that winter is upon us, it‚Äôs a good time to review how you'll be notified of school delays and closures.

How the decision to close schools is made:
To help make the best possible decision, weather forecasts are monitored throughout the process. District staff members drive the roads beginning at 3:30 am checking schools and routes that are frequently impacted and report road conditions to the superintendent. A decision and announcement to delay or close schools is usually made by 5:30 am.
Information is shared using these communication channels:
ÔÇ∑ FlashAlert, www.flashalert.net, Local TV, radio and newspaper pull information from FlashAlert. You can subscribe to receive text and email alerts from FlashAlert.
ÔÇ∑ Social Media
ÔÇ∑ District mobile app
ÔÇ∑ Email to families
ÔÇ∑ District website
We do not use our automated calling system to alert families of school delays and closures due to weather to avoid phone calls in the early morning hours. If no messages are posted, schools are open and operating on normal schedules.

post_text:
At the December 19, 2018 Board meeting Jeremy Toponce was sworn into office replacing Oscar Escalante representing Lakewood School Director District #1. Mr. Escalante resigned his Board position effective October 10, 2018. Mr. Toponce was selected from a field of two highly qualified applicants. He will serve on the board until the next regularly scheduled school board election that will be held during November of 2019.

Mr. Toponce has lived in the community with his wife Alysa for the past ten years. He is a local retailer and wife Alysa is a Paraeducator with Lakewood School District. They have 3 children, George a graduate from Lakewood High in 2018, Mason a Junior, and Maryjane a Sophomore.

He has been an active supporter of the Lakewood School District and we are delighted to welcome him into his new role as a board member!

Lakewood School District is happy to announce the rollout of our new app that sends push notifications during emergencies, part of the district‚Äôs efforts to upgrade its digital presence following the launch of our new website in August.

post_text: Good afternoon Lakewood families. With many classes having Harvest parties tomorrow, we wanted you to be aware of our district snack policy. If you are bringing in a treat to share with the class, we ask that you please choose a nut-free snack from our acceptable snack list which can be found on the district website under the ‚ÄúFor Families‚Äù tab. All snacks and treats must be in the original packaging that includes the ingredient and allergy information. No homemade or bakery items, please. ALL food items should be checked by the nurse, teacher or office staff before it‚Äôs allowed to be distributed in the classroom. If any food items that contain nuts or have been processed on equipment that may contain nuts, they will not be allowed.

post_text:
Congratulations to LHS Band Members accepted into NW Honor Band 2019

Congratulations to Junior, Daniel Henshaw(Clarinet) and Seniors, Isaiah Hogue (Bass Clarinet), Tyler Rahberger (Trumpet) and Alex Williams (Trombone) for being accepted into NW Honor Band 2019. These 4 amazing musicians will spend 2 days in January practicing, learning and performing with the best high school musicians in the NW!
This year the NW Honor Bands will be instructed and conducted by Dr. Donald J. McKinney - Director of Bands at the University of Colorado Boulder and
Dr. Jaclyn Hartenberger - Director of Bands at the University of Georgia.

This is a GREAT accomplishment for these four hard-working, talented young men!
